headline: The Score: Morgan Stanley, Porsche, Broadcom, Walmart and More Stocks That Defined the Week
summary: Porsche   wants a new driver to get the German automaker back on course.  Porsche said Friday that it would start talks with Chief Executive  Oliver Blume  about an early exit, and with former McLaren Automotive boss  Michael Leiters  about taking the wheel.  Blume is also CEO of Volkswagen—Porsche’s majority owner—and his dual role has long attracted criticism.

headline: Week’s Best: Big Jump in Schwab Referral Minimums
summary: Charles Schwab  is increasing the minimum investible-asset levels for clients to participate in the Schwab Advisor Network, or SAN.  Investors once again find themselves in the midst of a Federal Reserve rate-lowering cycle.  On Sept. 17, the Fed lowered the federal-funds rate by a quarter point and signaled that two more cuts are likely by year end.

headline: Morgan Stanley Looks to Raise $7.5 Billion From Bond Sale
summary: Morgan Stanley’s deal follows a $10 billion sale on Tuesday by Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and a $5 billion deal by JPMorgan Chase & Co. on Wednesday.  The average yield for US investment-grade bonds hit a one-year low of 4.69% on Thursday while spreads remain at historically low levels of below 0.8 percentage point, meaning funding costs remain attractive for higher-rated borrowers.  Morgan Stanley’s deal is the only one in the market this Friday.

headline: Morgan Stanley (MS) Margin Increase Reinforces Bullish Narratives Despite Slower Forward Growth
summary: Morgan Stanley (MS) posted a net profit margin of 22.7%, up from last year’s 18.2%, translating into a robust 46.6% jump in earnings year over year. This far outpaces its five-year average growth rate of just 0.5% per year. Despite the solid growth, Wall Street will note that forward-looking expectations are more muted, with management guiding for 4.1% annual earnings growth and 4.7% annual revenue growth, both below the broader US market's projected rates.
